The Trico Products accidental release prevention policy involves a unified approach that integrates technology, procedures, and management practices.  This emergency response policy involves the preparation of a response plan that is tailored to each facility and to the emergency response services available in the community.  The policy adheres to EPA prevention Program procedures where applicable, and is compliance with EPA emergency response program requirements.

The Trico Products facility is located at 1995 Billy Mitchell Boulevard, Brownsville, Cameron County, Texas.  The sintering furnace operation utilizes anhydrous ammonia in its process.  This process chemical, the regulated substance handled, is stored in a single horizontal tank located on the northwest side of the property.  The tank has a manual shutoff valves in case of an emergency.  The facility is manned 24-hours a day and the tank has a fence perimeter to prevent entry from un-authorized personnel.  The anhydrous ammonia process is checked routinely throughout the day.  Self-contained-breathing-apparatus (SCBA) are stored strategically throughout the facility.

The Trico Products accidental release prevention program is based on the following key elements.

- Strong adherence to Process Safety Management;
- High level of training of the operators;
- Preventive maintenance program;
- Use of process and safety equiptment;
- Use of accurate and effective operating procedures;
- Performance of a hazard review assessment of equiptment and procedures; and
- Implementation of an audit and inspection program.

Chemical specific prevention steps include availability of self-contained-breathing-apparatus, Level B protective clothing, and awareness of the hazardous and toxic properties of anhydrous ammonia.

No accidental releases of anhydrous ammonia have occurred in the past five years.

